<span class="text">
Senior technology and management executives from government and industry will gather during the 2008 International CES to share ideas with elected officials, candidates and political experts at CES Government 2008.&nbsp;The conference focus this year is the November 2008 elections and their impact on government technology budgets, programs and planning.<BR><BR>Focused discussions, substantive keynote and executive plenary sessions and unique networking opportunities&nbsp;provides conference participants opportunities to match the critical intersect of government management and technology applications with significant government challenges. The conference features leaders from both political parties and addresses: 
<UL>
<LI>Election forecasts and what they could mean for IT budgets and the application of information technologies to government priorities </LI>
<LI>The presidential transition: effective strategies to ensure that the right person gets the right job </LI>
<LI>How to plan for or protect programs:&nbsp; What industry can do - What government can do </LI>
<LI>State government election forecast and the outlook for substantive, budget-driven initiatives in identity management, law enforcement and homeland security, social services and health care </LI>
<LI>Likely winners and losers </LI>
<LI>Market research conducted and presented at conference open identifying perceptions and trends of public and private sector IT executives on the impact of the ‘08 elections<BR></LI></UL>
<BLOCKQUOTE><SPAN class=subhead>TUESDAY, JANUARY 8, 2008<BR>REGISTRATION OPENS<BR></SPAN>
<TABLE cellSpacing=1 cellPadding=1 width="90%" border=1>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;3-7 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top>
<P><SPAN class=subhead>Badge pick up available</SPAN><BR>Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas,&nbsp;Foyer, Salons I &amp; II*.<BR></P></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;5-7 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Conference Welcome Reception</SPAN><BR>The Pavilion, Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas<BR></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>*Badge pick up for International CES and CES Government available at all <A href="/faqs/general.asp#1436">CES badge pick up locations</A> starting Saturday, January 5, 2008. <BR><SPAN class=subhead><BR>WEDNESDAY JANUARY 9, 2008<BR>DAY 1 OF CES GOVERNMENT<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=1 cellPadding=1 width="90%" border=1 vAlign="top">
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top width="20%">7:30-8:15 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Registration and Continental Breakfast</SPAN><BR>Foyer, Salons I &amp; II</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>8:15-8:30 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Welcome</SPAN><BR><STRONG>Donald W. Upson<BR>ICG Government</STRONG><BR>Salons I &amp; II</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>8:30-9:05 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Perspectives and Promises: </SPAN><SPAN class=subhead>Where Candidates Stand on IT and Management</SPAN><BR><STRONG>Bruce McConnell<BR>President, Government Futures<BR>Former Director of Technology Policy, OMB</STRONG><BR>Bruce McConnell opens CES Government with the release of provocative and surprising data surrounding candidate perceptions and policy positions on technology and management in government.&nbsp;&nbsp; Government IT veteran McConnell also will identify those IT and management employee positions perceived as key to a new administration, programs likely to carry large IT visibility and budgets and those that may become less important&nbsp;&nbsp; Following this presentation, conference attendees will receive his research.&nbsp; It also will be distributed to both political parties, candidate organizations and select, senior elected and appointed officials in state and Federal jurisdictions.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>9:05-9:40 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Opening Keynote - </SPAN><SPAN class=subhead>Making Them Get IT: Technology as a Priority Policy</SPAN><BR><STRONG>The Honorable Mark Warner<BR>Former Governor, Commonwealth of Virginia<BR>Current Candidate, US Senate</STRONG><BR>Governor Warner Governor Warner incorporated major technology agendas into his successful gubernatorial bid, and then put in place a program of technology-based government reform that won his state the designation of “Best Managed State in America.”&nbsp; His 21st century technology focus also helped him ascend to Chairman of the National Governor’s Association.&nbsp; Governor Warner will discuss his views on technology and management in government, and his perspectives on the role technology and management can and should play in state and Federal 08’ elections.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;9:45-10:15 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Technology's Mission Focus: Know Your Customer<BR></SPAN><STRONG>Dan Blair<BR>Chairman<BR>US Postal Regulatory Commission</STRONG><BR>The Postal Service is one of the largest users of technology and Dan Blair has been involved with the acquisition, application and management of technology to postal services for most of his career.&nbsp; His tenure as the deputy at OPM also gives him insight into workforce and management challenges faced by government generally.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>10-10:15 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Break</SPAN></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>10:15-11 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Bits and Bytes vs. Vision</SPAN><BR><STRONG>The Honorable Paul Brubaker<BR>Administrator<BR>Research and Innovative Technology Administration</STRONG><BR>As a Senate subcommittee staff director, Mr. Brubaker produced and distributed the “Computer Chaos” report.&nbsp; This report was the basis for the Clinger-Cohen Act of which Brubaker was a principal staff architect.&nbsp; Today Mr. Brubaker brings his recipe of vision to an otherwise obscure agency within the Department of Transportation.&nbsp;&nbsp; His perspectives on Clinger-Cohen, and now Intelligent Transportation and alternative fuels, stand as case studies in advancing technology-based agendas to matters of national debate and awareness.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>11-11:30 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Gotcha!&nbsp; How To Navigate Today’s Challenging Ethics Environment</SPAN><BR><SPAN class=text_colored>The evolving ethics environment in government and the fine lines between what can and should be done, and what can and should not.</SPAN><BR><STRONG>Stephen Ryan, Former Chief Counsel to the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,&nbsp; Partner, McDermitt, Will &amp; Emory</STRONG><BR>Public and private sector officials alike are increasingly confronted with and confused by an always changing ethics environment.&nbsp; Ryan served as principal staff author of many laws governing procurement ethics and program oversight.&nbsp; He will bring his three decades of government experience together in a focused discussion of steps public and private sector executives to take to ensure sound ethical practices and protect against violations and scandal.&nbsp; He also will talk about the role of ethics in the transition to a new administration.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>11:45 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Luncheon</SPAN></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD>12:30-1:30 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Luncheon Keynote</SPAN><BR><SPAN class=text_colored>Critical Crossroads: Effective support needed for IT and Management in Government</SPAN><BR><STRONG>The Honorable Tom Davis, Vice Chairman, House Government Reform Committee</STRONG><BR>Long recognized as the leading voice in Congress on issues of procurement, government technology and management, Davis takes a critical look at why the application of technology to government challenges is not a higher priority.&nbsp; He will focus on industry-government collaboration, the need for enhanced authority for CIOs, and the erosion of effective and organized efforts to support and advance programs and processes vital to the application of technology to critical government priorities.&nbsp; <BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>1:30-2:10 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>The State-Federal Relationship: Making it Work Better</SPAN><BR><STRONG>The Honorable Anne Petera<BR>Assistant Secretary, Interngovernmental Programs, Department of Homeland Security</STRONG>&nbsp;<BR>From Federal to state to local government, jurisdictions are struggling with improved connections on critical priorities of homeland security, law enforcement, health care and social services.&nbsp; State-Federal relations in homeland security especially loom large in the 08’ political debate and landscape.&nbsp; Anne Petera is point for that homeland security relationship and brings to her position a long career of senior executive experience in both state and Federal governments.&nbsp; Her current position provides a case study through which she will share her experience and outlook on where that relationship stands today and how it may look tomorrow.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>2:10-2:45p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Afternoon Keynote<BR></SPAN><STRONG>The Honorable Lurita Doan<BR>Administrator, General Services Administration<BR></STRONG>GSA manages the government’s largest buying vehicle and remains at the center of major procurement reform.&nbsp; The acquisition environment is changing and many believe commercial buying practices are at risk.&nbsp; Administrator Doan is an advocate for commercial practices and will give her perspective on the current state and outlook of procurement policy.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;2:45-p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Break</SPAN></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>3-4:15 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>CIO Firing Line</SPAN><BR><STRONG>Select Government CIOs and other Senior Government executives attending CES Government will participate in this conference highlight.</STRONG> <BR>A CES Government highlight, select CIOs and senior government executives attending CES Government will participate in this tight and highly interactive roundtable where rapid fire-questions will be posed to individuals CIOs and other government executives, as well as the collective group.&nbsp; Electronic voting will allow anonymity on appropriate group questions.&nbsp; Areas addressed will include political vs. career CIO, effectiveness of industry program support, procurement processes, Congress and oversight, IT and program funding, ethics and 08’ election outlook.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>4:15-4:45 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Ask The Chairman</SPAN><BR><STRONG>The Honorable Henry Waxman (invited)<BR>Chairman<BR>House Government Reform Committee</STRONG><BR>Chairman Waxman brings strong perspective on government procurement and public-private sector collaboration to his role as Chairman of the House Government Reform Committee.&nbsp; He will share his views on his 2008 Committee agenda, outlook for the new session of Congress and the role of oversight in the 08 elections.&nbsp; Questions will be posed to the Chairman on a range of issues from procurement to outsourcing.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>4:45 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>First Day Closes</SPAN></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>5:30-7:30 p.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>CES Government Speakers Reception</SPAN><BR>Florentine Gardens, Ritz Carlton Lake Las Vegas&nbsp;<BR></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></SPAN><BR><BR><SPAN class=subhead>THURSDAY, JANUARY 10, 2008<BR>DAY 2 OF CES GOVERNMENT<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=1 cellPadding=1 width="90%" border=1>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD width="20%">&nbsp;7:15-8:30 a.m.</TD>
<TD><SPAN class=subhead>Networking Breakfast Reception</SPAN><BR>Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas, Salon I</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;8:35 a.m.</TD>
<TD vAlign=top><SPAN class=subhead>Departure for Las Vegas Convention Center<BR></SPAN>Lobby, Ritz-Carlton Lake Las Vegas</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD vAlign=top>&nbsp;9:15-9:30 a.m.</TD>
